# Google Apps Script Core Rule

Follow these standards when generating or changing code in this repository.

## Runtime Constraints

- Target Google Apps Script runtime APIs; do not assume Node runtime APIs are available.
- Do not use filesystem access in Apps Script code.
- Avoid unsupported browser APIs in server-side code.
- Keep dependencies minimal and compatible with Apps Script execution limits.

## Code Organization

- Keep Apps Script entry points in `main.ts` (for example `doGet`, `onOpen`, `onEdit`).
- Put business logic in `services/`.
- Keep reusable helpers in `utils/`.
- Keep sheet access helpers separate from domain logic.

## Google Sheets Performance

- Batch reads and writes whenever possible.
- Do not call `getRange` inside write loops when a single `setValues` call can be used.
- Minimize API calls inside loops.

## Configuration and Secrets

- Never hardcode secrets, tokens, or environment-specific IDs.
- Use `PropertiesService` for configuration and sensitive values.
- Keep constants limited to safe, non-secret values.

## UI and Error Handling

- Use HTML Service for UI surfaces and `google.script.run` for client-server calls.
- Return safe, user-friendly error messages to the frontend.
- Do not expose stack traces, secrets, or raw sensitive responses to users.

## Security and Reliability

- Validate inputs from sidebars, dialogs, forms, and web app requests.
- Avoid logging sensitive user or business data.
- Prefer least-privilege behavior and safe defaults for data-changing operations.

## Delivery Workflow

- Make small, testable changes instead of large one-shot rewrites.
- Compile TypeScript before `clasp push`.
- Call out Apps Script platform constraints when they affect implementation choices.

## PRD Change Control

- When editing `docs/PRD.md`, always update the PRD change table at the bottom of the document in the same change.
- Add one new row per PRD update with date, version, summary of change, and author/owner.
- If the change table does not exist yet, create it at the bottom of `docs/PRD.md` before completing the PRD edit.
- For any implemented functionality change (not just docs edits), update `docs/PRD.md` in the same change, including a version bump and change-log row.
- Keep `src/Code.js` `APP_METADATA_.PRD_VERSION` exactly in sync with the version at the top of `docs/PRD.md` in every change.
- Any code change is blocked until all three are updated together: `docs/PRD.md` content, PRD version number, and `src/Code.js` `APP_METADATA_.PRD_VERSION`.

### PRD version in file headers (clasp / Apps Script)

**FOS Dashboard (`FOSDashboard` repo):** The product PRD is **`docs/FOS-Dashboard-PRD.md`**. Whenever its **version number** (header line `Version X.Y`) changes:

1. Bump **`FOS_PRD_VERSION`** in `src/Code.js` to match **exactly**.
2. Update the **PRD version line** at the top of **every** clasp-pushed file under `src/` (**all** `.js` and `.html`; **exclude** `appsscript.json`):
   - **JavaScript:** first line inside the top `/**` block: ` * PRD version X.Y — sync with docs/FOS-Dashboard-PRD.md` (example: **1.5**).
   - **HTML:** immediately after `<!DOCTYPE html>`: `<!-- PRD version X.Y — sync with docs/FOS-Dashboard-PRD.md -->` (same **X.Y** as the PRD file).
3. Include these header updates in the **same** change as the PRD version bump and changelog row.

**Other harpin Apps Script projects** (e.g. Clockify–Fibery sync): may follow `docs/PRD.md` and `APP_METADATA_.PRD_VERSION` per that project’s rules; apply the same “every pushed `src` file” header discipline using **that** repo’s PRD path.

## Feature Spec Template Compliance

- All new feature documents in `docs/features/` must follow `docs/FEATURE_TEMPLATE.md`.
- Use the same section order and headings from the template unless the user explicitly requests a deviation.
- Keep template checklists as markdown checkboxes (`- [ ]`) so progress can be tracked.
- Name feature files using the existing numeric convention (for example `001-feature-name.md`).
- If a feature spec exists but does not match the template, update it to template format when making substantive edits.
